  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "31. Nibhaz—under that of a dog—that Egyptian form of animal-worship having prevailed in ancient Syria, as is evident from the image of a large dog at the mouth of the Nahr-el-Kelb, or Dog river.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Tartak—According to the rabbis, it was in the form of an ass, but others understand it as a planet of ill-omen, probably Saturn.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Adrammelech—supposed by some to be the same as Molech, and in Assyrian mythology to stand for the sun. It was worshipped in the form of a mule—others maintain in that of a peacock.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Anammelech—worshipped in the form of a hare; others say in that of a goat.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
